  "texts": [
    "◁ Fact 2.10 (Powerset Possibilization).",
    "For any world frame F and world model M = ⟨F, V⟩:1. for any X ∈ M ℘ and φ ∈ L(Φ, I), M ℘, X ⊩ φ iff ∀x ∈ X, M, x ⊨ φ; 2. for any Σ ⊆ L(Φ, I), Σ is satisfiable over F ℘ iff Σ is satisfiable over F.Proof.",
    "Part 1 is provable by an easy induction on φ.For part 2, if Σ is satisfied at a world w in a world model M based on F, then by part 1, Σ is satisfied at {w} in M ℘, which is easily seen to be an admissible model based on F ℘.",
    "In the other direction, for any partial-state model M = ⟨F ℘, π⟩ based on F ℘, the world model M -℘ = ⟨F, π -℘ ⟩ defined by w ∈ π -℘ (p) iff {w} ∈ π(p) is easily seen to be an admissible model based on F. Moreover, (M -℘) ℘ = M, so if Σ is satisfied at a state X in M, then part 1 implies that there is an x ∈ X such that Σ is satisfied at x in M -℘.",
    "From Fact 2.10.2 and the fact that K is the logic of (full) world frames, we have the following.Corollary 2.11 (Logics of Powerset Possibilizations)."
  ],
  "correct_citations": []
}